[[File:SportsLegendsMuseumCamdenYards.jpg|thumb|300px|'''Sports Legends Museum''' at the former [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad|B&O Railroad]]'s [[Camden Station]]]]
'''Sports Legends Museum at Camden Yards''' was a non-profit sports museum in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], [[United States]], owned and operated by the [[Babe Ruth Birthplace Museum|Babe Ruth Birthplace & Museum]]. It opened on May 14, 2005, with the daughter of celebrated baseball player [[Babe Ruth]] in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stiehm|first=Jamie|date=May 15, 2005|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2005-05-15/news/0505150018_1_babe-ruth-museum-legends-museum-legends-at-camden|title=Sports history hits home at museum|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|page=1B|accessdate=2009-05-06}}</ref> After ten years of operation the museum closed abruptly on October 12, 2015 after failing to reach an agreement with the [[Maryland Stadium Authority]] for the continued use of Camden Station.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-sports-legends-museum-closes-20151012-story.html|title = Sports Legends Museum closes its doors|last = Sherman|first = Natalie|last2 = Encina|first2 = Eduardo A.|date = 2015-10-12|work = The Baltimore Sun|first3 = Jeff| last3 = Barker|access-date = 2016-03-06}}</ref> The {{convert|22000|sqft|0|sing=on}} museum was adjacent to the main gate of [[Oriole Park at Camden Yards]] and had artifacts and interactive exhibits profiling Maryland’s sports history. Exhibits included such area teams as the [[Baltimore Orioles]], [[Baltimore Ravens]], [[History of the Indianapolis Colts|Baltimore Colts]], [[Maryland Terrapins]], [[Baltimore Elite Giants]], [[Baltimore Black Sox]], and the [[Baltimore Blast]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lyght|first=Daniel|date=July 28, 2004| title=Camden Yards expansion gives Ruth Museum a place to grow|work=The Baltimore Sun|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2004-07-28/sports/0407280228_1_babe-ruth-birthplace-camden-yards-ruth-museum|page=1C|accessdate=2009-05-06}}</ref>
The museum was housed in the former [[Camden Station]], originally constructed in 1857 by the [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] (B&O) as its main passenger station in Baltimore. After being vacant since the 1980s, the depot's exterior was restored in the 1990s as part of the development of the [[Camden Yards Sports Complex]]. Later interior renovations and remodeling were made to accommodate the building's adaptive reuse as a sports museum. [[Geppi's Entertainment Museum]], which opened in September 2006, is located on the upper level of the building, directly above where Sports Legends at Camden Yards was. The nearby Babe Ruth Birthplace & Museum remains in existence as a separate museum on Emory Street, two and a half blocks from Camden Station.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sports Legends has Moved Out|url=http://baberuthmuseum.org/sports-legends-moving/|website=Babe Ruth Birthplace and Sports Legends Museums|publisher=Babe Ruth Birthplace Foundation, Inc.|date=12 October 2015}}</ref>
A replica of the [[Vince Lombardi Trophy]] from [[Super Bowl V]] is part of the museum's collection.<ref name="Simers">{{cite news|last1=Simers|first1=T.J.|authorlink1=T. J. Simers|title=There Are Many Who Believe Georgia Is the Original Trophy Wife|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/jan/29/sports/sp-58976|accessdate=3 October 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=29 January 2000}}</ref> The original trophy from the Colts' 1971 [[Super Bowl]] victory was taken by former owner [[Carroll Rosenbloom]]<ref name="Simers" /> after he traded the Colts for the [[Los Angeles Rams]] in 1972.<ref>{{cite news|title=Big Deals|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-02-28/sports/sp-41136_1_los-angeles-rams|accessdate=3 October 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=28 February 1996|quote=* July 13, 1972--Los Angeles Rams part-owner Robert Irsay purchases the remaining $19 million in stock and swaps franchises with Baltimore Colt owner Carroll Rosenbloom.}}</ref> A replica trophy was later made for the Colts, but in the [[Baltimore Colts relocation to Indianapolis|Midnight Move of 1984]], the team was not allowed to keep the trophy. That trophy stayed in the city of Baltimore's possession, and was placed in the Sports Legends Museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baberuthmuseum.org/exhibit/almost-religion-baltimores-colts/|title=Almost Religion: Baltimore's Colts|website=Babe Ruth Birthplace and Sports Legends Museums|publisher=Babe Ruth Birthplace Foundation, Inc.|accessdate=2011-02-28}}</ref>
