{{Infobox Organization |name = Turkish Confederation of Businessmen and Industrialists (TUSKON) |image = |image_border = |size = |caption = |map = |msize = |mcaption = |motto = |formation = 2005 |extinction = 27 July 2016 |type = Union of employers |headquarters = [[Şişli]], [[Istanbul]] |location = Turkey |membership = |language = |leader_title = |leader_name = Rızanur Meral |key_people = |num_staff = |budget = |website = [https://web.archive.org/web/20060411090254/http://www.tuskon.org:80/ www.tuskon.org] }}
The '''Turkish Confederation of Businessmen and Industrialists''' ({{lang-tr|'''Türkiye İşadamları ve Sanayiciler Konfederasyonu'''}}), best known by the abbreviation '''TUSKON''', was a [[employers' organization]] in [[Turkey]], with about 40,000 members. It was founded in 2005 by seven business federations.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Christopher Holton|author2=Clare Lopez|title=The Gulen Movement|url=https://www.centerforsecuritypolicy.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Gulen_Final.pdf|work=Center for Security Policy|accessdate=2 August 2016|date=December 2015}}</ref> Ninety percent of the TUSKON members were small or medium establishments with fewer than 50 employees. TUSKON engaged in [[lobbying]] all decision-makers at the local, regional, national and global levels.<ref name=Kurumsal>[http://www.tuskon.org/?p=content&cl=kurumsal&l=kurumsal Tuskon Website]</ref> Rızanur Meral, the managing director of SANKO Automotive Group, was the last president of TUSKON.<ref name="sab">{{cite news|title=TUSKON tarih oldu|url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/ekonomi/2016/07/24/tuskon-tarih-oldu|accessdate=2 August 2016|work=Sabah|date=24 July 2016|language=Turkish}}</ref>
TUSKON was closely connected to the Islamic [[Gülen movement]] of the Turkish preacher [[Fethullah Gülen]].<ref name="AlMonitor">{{cite news|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/04/turkey-business-clash-gulen-akp.html|title=Clash of the Anatolian Tigers|date=28 April 2014|author=Pinar Tremblay|work=Al-Monitor|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2014/05/01/businessmen-quit-gulenaffiliated-organizations|title= Businessmen quit Gülen-affiliated organizations|newspaper=Daily Sabah|date=30 April 2014|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref> The movement controlled many businesses and organizations around the world, with many of their leaders having membership in TUSKON, such as [[Bank Asya]].<ref name="AlMonitor"/> TUSKON was closed following the [[2016 Turkish coup d'état attempt|coup attempt]] in July 2016.<ref name="sab"/>
