'''William Henry Bell''' was the head of the [[Asiatic Petroleum Company]] and member of the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Council]] and the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]].

==Biography==
He joined the Asiatic Petroleum Company and became the manager and then head of the oil company in South China and the Philippines.<ref name="wed"/> He represented the company in the [[Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce]] and elected as chairman in 1935.<ref>{{cite web|title=Past Chairmen|work=The Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce|url=http://www.chamber.org.hk/en/about/hkgcc_chairman_vice-chairman-4.aspx|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref> He was also directors of other public companies including director of the [[Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation]].

He was appointed to the Legislative Council on several occasions. In May 1931, he elected by the Justices of Peace to be their representatives on the Legislative Council during [[Henry Pollock]]'s absence.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The China Mail|date=9 May 1931|title=Council Election.|page=1}}</ref> He was again appointed to the Legislative Council in April 1932<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=8 April 1932|number=216}}</ref> and April 1934.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=20 April 1934|number=312}}</ref> In 1935, he was elected by the Chamber of Commerce on 15 April in succession of [[C. Gordon Mackie]] who retired and left Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The China Mail|date=16 April 1935|title=H.K. Chamber of Commerce|page=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The China Mail|date=20 April 1935|title=Council Meeting|page=15}}</ref> In 1936, he was appointed to the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Council]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=9 June 1936|number=532}}</ref>

He was also member of the many government agencies, such as the Harbour Board,<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=24 December 1930|number=771}}</ref> the Authorized Architects' Committee and Consulting Committee,<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=14 February 1933|number=118}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=15 April 1932|number=232}}</ref> and the Licensing Board.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=26 April 1935|number=342}}</ref> He was also nominated by the government to the Court of the [[University of Hong Kong]] in 1934.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Hongkong Government Gazette|work=The Hongkong Government|date=2 January 1935|number=8}}</ref>

Bell retired from the Legislative Council in July 1936 and continued to serve on the Executive Council until November when he returned to England.<ref name="departure">{{cite news|newspaper=The Hong Kong Telegraph|date=25 November 1936|title=Loss to Hong Kong|page=12}}</ref> Tribute was paid by Governor Sir [[Andrew Caldecott]] and member of the Legislative Council [[John Johnstone Paterson]] for his works on the legislature.<ref name="departure"/> In November 1936, he left by the [[SS President Coolidge|SS ''President Coolidge'']] for America and England.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=15 November 1936|page=1|title=MR. W. H. BELL}}</ref>

His first wife, Dora Bell, died in November 1933.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Hong Kong Telegraph|date=25 November 1933|title=Late Mrs. W. H. Bell|page=5}}</ref> He later married to Helen Joyce Calkin, third daughter of Walter L. Calkiin of Hightrees, Ashley Road, [[Walton-on-Thames]], in 1935 at Hong Kong.<ref name="wed">{{cite news|newspaper=Hong Kong Daily Press|date=11 March 1935|title=Mr. W. H. Bell to Wed|page=7}}</ref>

